This paper deals with person re-identification (ReID) algorithms, which are commonly studied in the computer vision (CV) field. The paper proposes an unsupervised domain adaptive ReID feature learning framework, which involves transfer learning and domain adaptation techniques. Therefore, the paper is likely to belong to the Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition (cs.CV) sub-category. Additionally, the paper involves machine learning techniques such as adversarial discriminative domain adaptation, which falls under the sub-category of Machine Learning (cs.LG). The paper also deals with large-scale datasets, which could fall under the sub-category of Multimedia (cs.MM). The paper involves the use of attributes to describe the semantic appearance of a person, which could fall under the sub-category of Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI). Finally, the paper involves the use of adversarial techniques, which could fall under the sub-category of Cryptography and Security (cs.CR).
